    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Some Wisdom From Korea</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter discusses Esther Kim's sacrifice of place on Olympic tae kwon do team for friend and competitor; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>I admire the tae kwan do athlete Esther Kim for her heart but I am impressed more by the power of her home education (''An Athlete's Sacrifice for an Injured Competitor,'' May 25). As a Korean-born American, I can see that her father probably taught her the same wisdom that my father gave me when I was young.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>I admire the tae kwan do athlete Esther Kim for her heart but I am impressed more by the power of her home education (''An Athlete's Sacrifice for an Injured Competitor,'' May 25). As a Korean-born American, I can see that her father probably taught her the same wisdom that my father gave me when I was young.</p>
        <p>Many Korean fathers teach their children to feed strangers or guests first, even if there is no food to feed yourself. Kim's decision didn't come from a woman's heart (while there are no records of this); her Korean wisdom drove her to make that decision.</p>
        <p>SUNNY PARK  Atlanta</p>
      </block>
